1
0:00:12.16,000 --> 0:00:15,000
There's an old saying, "Just because you can't see something,

2
0:00:15.16,000 --> 0:00:18,000
doesn't mean it's not there."

3
0:00:18.16,000 --> 0:00:25,000
My work is -- it's a reflection of myself.

4
0:00:25.16,000 --> 0:00:29,000
What I wanted to do is to

5
0:00:29.16,000 --> 0:00:34,000
show the world that the little things

6
0:00:34.16,000 --> 0:00:37,000
can be the biggest things.

7
0:00:37.16,000 --> 0:00:4,000
We all seem to think that,

8
0:00:40.16,000 --> 0:00:46,000
you know, if we look down on the ground, there's nothing there.

9
0:00:46.16,000 --> 0:00:49,000
And we use the word "nothing."

10
0:00:49.16,000 --> 0:00:52,000
Nothing doesn't exist, because there is always something.

11
0:00:52.16,000 --> 0:00:54,000
My mother told me that, when I was a child,

12
0:00:54.16,000 --> 0:00:59,000
that I should always respect the little things.

13
0:00:59.16,000 --> 0:01:01,000
What made me do this work? I shall go into my story.

14
0:01:03.16,000 --> 0:01:07,000
This all started when I was age five.

15
0:01:07.16,000 --> 0:01:1,000
What made me do it? At school, I will admit this:

16
0:01:10.16,000 --> 0:01:13,000
academically, I couldn't express myself.

17
0:01:13.16,000 --> 0:01:18,000
So I was, more or less, classed as "nothing."

18
0:01:18.16,000 --> 0:01:23,000
My world was seen as less.

19
0:01:23.16,000 --> 0:01:27,000
So I decided I didn't really want to be a part of that world.

20
0:01:27.16,000 --> 0:01:31,000
I thought, I need to retreat

21
0:01:31.16,000 --> 0:01:33,000
into something else.

22
0:01:33.16,000 --> 0:01:36,000
So when my mother used to take me to school,

23
0:01:36.16,000 --> 0:01:38,000
she thought I was at school,

24
0:01:38.16,000 --> 0:01:41,000
and I used to do a U-turn, when her back was turned,

25
0:01:41.16,000 --> 0:01:45,000
and run off and hide in the shed at the back of the garden.

26
0:01:45.16,000 --> 0:01:5,000
Now, the one time I was in the shed,

27
0:01:50.16,000 --> 0:01:53,000
and my mother suspected something,

28
0:01:53.16,000 --> 0:01:55,000
thinking I was at school.

29
0:01:55.16,000 --> 0:01:59,000
My mother was like the woman in Tom and Jerry.

30
0:01:59.16,000 --> 0:02:02,000
So you'd just see her feet.

31
0:02:02.16,000 --> 0:02:06,000
(Laughter)

32
0:02:06.16,000 --> 0:02:1,000
So I was hiding in the shed, like that.

33
0:02:10.16,000 --> 0:02:15,000
And all of a sudden ...

34
0:02:15.16,000 --> 0:02:19,000
And then I saw her legs.

35
0:02:19.16,000 --> 0:02:22,000
And then she said -- grabbed me like that, because my mother was quite big --

36
0:02:22.16,000 --> 0:02:25,000
and she lifted me up and she says,

37
0:02:25.16,000 --> 0:02:27,000
"How come you're not at school?"

38
0:02:27.16,000 --> 0:02:3,000
I told her I couldn't face it because the way

39
0:02:30.16,000 --> 0:02:33,000
the teacher was treating me, ridiculing me,

40
0:02:33.16,000 --> 0:02:36,000
and using me as an example of failure.

41
0:02:36.16,000 --> 0:02:38,000
So I told her.

42
0:02:38.16,000 --> 0:02:42,000
At that age, obviously, I couldn't express it that way,

43
0:02:42.16,000 --> 0:02:45,000
but I told her I didn't feel right.

44
0:02:45.16,000 --> 0:02:47,000
And then she just said, "You're going back to school tomorrow."

45
0:02:47.16,000 --> 0:02:49,000
And walked off. And I didn't expect that,

46
0:02:49.16,000 --> 0:02:53,000
because I expected one of these ...

47
0:02:53.16,000 --> 0:02:55,000
But I didn't get it.

48
0:02:55.16,000 --> 0:02:57,000
So I'm sitting there thinking.

49
0:02:57.16,000 --> 0:03:01,000
And as I looked down on the ground,

50
0:03:01.16,000 --> 0:03:05,000
I noticed there was some ants running around.

51
0:03:05.16,000 --> 0:03:07,000
And I went into this little fantasy world.

52
0:03:07.16,000 --> 0:03:09,000
And I thought,

53
0:03:09.16,000 --> 0:03:14,000
"These ants, are they looking for the queen ant?

54
0:03:14.16,000 --> 0:03:16,000
Or do they need somewhere to live?"

55
0:03:16.16,000 --> 0:03:18,000
So I thought "Perhaps,

56
0:03:18.16,000 --> 0:03:22,000
if I made these ants some apartments,

57
0:03:22.16,000 --> 0:03:26,000
they'll move in."

58
0:03:26.16,000 --> 0:03:3,000
(Laughter)

59
0:03:30.16,000 --> 0:03:32,000
So I did.

60
0:03:32.16,000 --> 0:03:35,000
And how I set about that, I got some splinters of wood.

61
0:03:35.16,000 --> 0:03:38,000
And I sliced the little splinters of wood with a broken shard of glass,

62
0:03:38.16,000 --> 0:03:42,000
constructed this little apartment.

63
0:03:42.16,000 --> 0:03:47,000
Well it looked like a little shanty shed when I'd finished.

64
0:03:47.16,000 --> 0:03:49,000
But I thought, perhaps the ant won't know, it'll probably move in.

65
0:03:49.16,000 --> 0:03:51,000
And so they did.

66
0:03:51.16,000 --> 0:03:54,000
That was a bit crude, at the time. And I made all these little apartments

67
0:03:54.16,000 --> 0:03:58,000
and little merry-go-rounds, seesaws and swings, little ladders.

68
0:03:58.16,000 --> 0:04:02,000
And then I encouraged the ants to come 'round by putting sugar and things like that.

69
0:04:02.16,000 --> 0:04:08,000
And then I sat down and all the ants came along.

70
0:04:08.16,000 --> 0:04:11,000
And all I could hear was "Is this for us?"

71
0:04:11.16,000 --> 0:04:13,000
(Laughter)

72
0:04:13.16,000 --> 0:04:15,000
And I say, "Yes, they're all for you."

73
0:04:15.16,000 --> 0:04:19,000
And they moved in, and decided not to pay me any rent.

74
0:04:19.16,000 --> 0:04:22,000
(Laughter)

75
0:04:22.16,000 --> 0:04:25,000
And from there I was watching this little world.

76
0:04:25.16,000 --> 0:04:3,000
It became part of me.

77
0:04:30.16,000 --> 0:04:37,000
When I discovered that I had this gift,

78
0:04:37.16,000 --> 0:04:41,000
I wanted to experiment with this world

79
0:04:41.16,000 --> 0:04:43,000
that we can't see.

80
0:04:43.16,000 --> 0:04:46,000
So I realized that there was more to life

81
0:04:46.16,000 --> 0:04:5,000
than just everything that we see around us that's huge.

82
0:04:50.16,000 --> 0:04:55,000
So I started to educate myself on this molecular level.

83
0:04:55.16,000 --> 0:04:59,000
And as I got older, I continued. I showed my mother.

84
0:04:59.16,000 --> 0:05:01,000
My mother told me to take it smaller.

85
0:05:01.16,000 --> 0:05:05,000
Now I shall show you something here.

86
0:05:05.16,000 --> 0:05:08,000
And I'll explain.

87
0:05:08.16,000 --> 0:05:11,000
As you can see,

88
0:05:11.16,000 --> 0:05:13,000
that's a pinhead.

89
0:05:13.16,000 --> 0:05:17,000
(Laughter)

90
0:05:17.16,000 --> 0:05:25,000
(Applause)

91
0:05:25.16,000 --> 0:05:29,000
Now that is called the Huf Haus.

92
0:05:29.16,000 --> 0:05:31,000
The gentleman who commissioned me to do this

93
0:05:31.16,000 --> 0:05:34,000
was a gentleman called Peter Huf.

94
0:05:34.16,000 --> 0:05:38,000
And he says to me "Willard, can you put my house on a pinhead?"

95
0:05:38.16,000 --> 0:05:43,000
(Laughter)

96
0:05:43.16,000 --> 0:05:46,000
So I say, "How are you going to fit in there?"

97
0:05:46.16,000 --> 0:05:49,000
(Laughter)

98
0:05:49.16,000 --> 0:05:52,000
And then he said to me,

99
0:05:52.16,000 --> 0:05:55,000
"I don't believe you can do it. Can you really do it?"

100
0:05:55.16,000 --> 0:05:59,000
And I says, "Well, try me."

101
0:05:59.16,000 --> 0:06:05,000
And then he said, "But I don't believe that you can do this." So I said, "OK."

102
0:06:05.16,000 --> 0:06:07,000
So, to cut a long story short,

103
0:06:07.16,000 --> 0:06:09,000
I went home, went underneath the microscope,

104
0:06:09.16,000 --> 0:06:13,000
and I crushed up a piece of glass,

105
0:06:13.16,000 --> 0:06:15,000
crushed it up.

106
0:06:15.16,000 --> 0:06:17,000
And underneath the microscope

107
0:06:17.16,000 --> 0:06:19,000
there were splinters of glass.

108
0:06:19.16,000 --> 0:06:22,000
Some of them were quite jagged.

109
0:06:22.16,000 --> 0:06:24,000
So I was crushing up these pieces of glass,

110
0:06:24.16,000 --> 0:06:27,000
which, as you can see,

111
0:06:27.16,000 --> 0:06:29,000
that's the actual frame of the house.

112
0:06:29.16,000 --> 0:06:35,000
And the actual roof is made up of a fiber,

113
0:06:35.16,000 --> 0:06:38,000
which I found in my sister's old teddy bear.

114
0:06:38.16,000 --> 0:06:41,000
(Laughter)

115
0:06:41.16,000 --> 0:06:43,000
So I got the teddy bear and I said,

116
0:06:43.16,000 --> 0:06:46,000
"Do you mind if I pull out one of your fibers?"

117
0:06:46.16,000 --> 0:06:48,000
So I did.

118
0:06:48.16,000 --> 0:06:51,000
And I looked at it beneath the microscope. And some of it was flat.

119
0:06:51.16,000 --> 0:06:53,000
So I decided to slice these up

120
0:06:53.16,000 --> 0:06:55,000
with the tool that I make

121
0:06:55.16,000 --> 0:06:59,000
by -- I sharpen the end of a needle into a blade.

122
0:06:59.16,000 --> 0:07:01,000
And then I actually

123
0:07:01.16,000 --> 0:07:04,000
slow down my whole nervous system.

124
0:07:04.16,000 --> 0:07:07,000
And then I work between my heartbeat,

125
0:07:07.16,000 --> 0:07:1,000
I have one-and-a-half seconds

126
0:07:10.16,000 --> 0:07:12,000
to actually move.

127
0:07:12.16,000 --> 0:07:14,000
And at the same time I have to watch I don't inhale

128
0:07:14.16,000 --> 0:07:16,000
my own work, at the same time.

129
0:07:16.16,000 --> 0:07:19,000
(Laughter)

130
0:07:19.16,000 --> 0:07:25,000
(Applause)

131
0:07:25.16,000 --> 0:07:27,000
Because that has happened to me.

132
0:07:27.16,000 --> 0:07:31,000
(Laughter)

133
0:07:31.16,000 --> 0:07:34,000
So what I did, like I said, come back to the glass.

134
0:07:34.16,000 --> 0:07:36,000
I found these little bits of glass.

135
0:07:36.16,000 --> 0:07:39,000
And I had to make them square.

136
0:07:39.16,000 --> 0:07:41,000
So I'm thinking "How can I do this?"

137
0:07:41.16,000 --> 0:07:45,000
So what I did, I got an oilstone. Broke the edge of an oilstone off.

138
0:07:45.16,000 --> 0:07:49,000
And what I did, I took pieces of glass. And I started to rub them.

139
0:07:49.16,000 --> 0:07:52,000
I used a little tweezer which I made from a hair clip.

140
0:07:52.16,000 --> 0:07:56,000
And I built rubber around the end of the tweezer so it wouldn't crush the glass.

141
0:07:56.16,000 --> 0:08:01,000
And then I started rubbing, very very gently,

142
0:08:01.16,000 --> 0:08:05,000
till some of the edges were quite square. And then I constructed it.

143
0:08:05.16,000 --> 0:08:07,000
And how I constructed it,

144
0:08:07.16,000 --> 0:08:1,000
is by making grooves in the top of the pinhead.

145
0:08:10.16,000 --> 0:08:13,000
And then pushing the glass in with its own friction.

146
0:08:13.16,000 --> 0:08:16,000
And as I was doing it, what happened?

147
0:08:16.16,000 --> 0:08:2,000
The instrument that I used turned into a catapult.

148
0:08:20.16,000 --> 0:08:24,000
And it went like this ...

149
0:08:24.16,000 --> 0:08:27,000
And then that was it.

150
0:08:27.16,000 --> 0:08:28,000
(Laughter)

151
0:08:28.16,000 --> 0:08:3,000
Gone.

152
0:08:30.16,000 --> 0:08:32,000
So I'm thinking, "Mr. Huf isn't going to be very happy

153
0:08:32.16,000 --> 0:08:35,000
when I told him his house has gone to another,

154
0:08:35.16,000 --> 0:08:38,000
into the atmosphere somewhere."

155
0:08:38.16,000 --> 0:08:4,000
So to cut the story short,

156
0:08:40.16,000 --> 0:08:42,000
I decided that I had to go back and do it.

157
0:08:42.16,000 --> 0:08:45,000
So I found some more. And I decided to, sort of,

158
0:08:45.16,000 --> 0:08:47,000
construct it very, very slowly,

159
0:08:47.16,000 --> 0:08:5,000
holding my breath, working between my heartbeat,

160
0:08:50.16,000 --> 0:08:52,000
and making sure everything is leveled.

161
0:08:52.16,000 --> 0:08:56,000
Because it's such a small sculpture,

162
0:08:56.16,000 --> 0:08:58,000
nothing can go wrong.

163
0:08:58.16,000 --> 0:09:01,000
And I decided to build it up.

164
0:09:01.16,000 --> 0:09:04,000
Then I used fibers out of my jumper,

165
0:09:04.16,000 --> 0:09:06,000
which I held and stretched.

166
0:09:06.16,000 --> 0:09:08,000
And made the beams going around the house.

167
0:09:08.16,000 --> 0:09:1,000
And the actual windows and the balcony

168
0:09:10.16,000 --> 0:09:12,000
had to be sort of constructed.

169
0:09:12.16,000 --> 0:09:14,000
I used a money spider's web

170
0:09:14.16,000 --> 0:09:16,000
to actually attach certain things,

171
0:09:16.16,000 --> 0:09:18,000
which sent me insane.

172
0:09:18.16,000 --> 0:09:21,000
But I managed to do it.

173
0:09:21.16,000 --> 0:09:24,000
And when I finished it, I came back the next day.

174
0:09:24.16,000 --> 0:09:28,000
I noticed that the house was occupied.

175
0:09:28.16,000 --> 0:09:32,000
Have we ever heard of a dust mite?

176
0:09:32.16,000 --> 0:09:34,000
Darren dust mite and his family moved in.

177
0:09:34.16,000 --> 0:09:37,000
(Laughter)

178
0:09:37.16,000 --> 0:09:41,000
So basically I'd completed the house.

179
0:09:41.16,000 --> 0:09:44,000
And there you are.

180
0:09:44.16,000 --> 0:09:51,000
(Applause)

181
0:09:51.16,000 --> 0:09:53,000
(Laughter)

182
0:09:55.16,000 --> 0:09:57,000
Right. As you can see,

183
0:09:57.16,000 --> 0:10:01,000
Bart Simpson is having a little argument.

184
0:10:01.16,000 --> 0:10:04,000
I think they're arguing about the space on the pin.

185
0:10:04.16,000 --> 0:10:07,000
There's not enough room for the two of them.

